<DOC><DOCNO> AP890504-0091 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-89 1141EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-Afghanistan     05-04 0225</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Afghanistan,0231</SECOND><HEAD>Afghan Planes Said To Bomb Refugee Camp in Pakistan</HEAD><DATELINE>PESHAWAR, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   An Afghan warplane bombed a refugeecamp in Pakistan today, killing three Afghans and injuring 16,officials said.   The warplane was one of two that flew over the Gambila refugeecamp this morning, 70 miles east of the Afghanistan border,officials in Pakistan's North West Frontier Province said oncondition of anonymity.   One plane dropped a bomb that destroyed six houses and left acrater 20-feet wide, the officials said. Seven of the injured werein serious condition.   Pakistan supports the Moslem guerrillas fighting the communistgovernment in Kabul and shelters more than 3 million refugees ofthe 11-year Afghan civil war. Many of the guerrilla leaders arebased in Pakistan.   Today's incursion by Afghan warplanes was the first reportedsince last fall. The Foreign Ministry is expected to lodge aprotest with the Afghan government as it has after previous airraids.   On Wednesday, Afghanistan accused Pakistan of helping theguerrillas prepare new attacks on the Afghan cities of Jalalabadand Kandahar.   The Moslem guerrillas have besieged Jalalabad since March 6,about three weeks after Soviet forces ended nine years ofintervention in the war. Pakistan funnels mainly-U.S. arms to theguerrillas. Kabul has warned the war may spill over into Pakistanunless Islamabad stops helping the guerrillas.</TEXT></DOC>